# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for this Next.js 15.5.12 project using the App Router.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version ^1.3.1 using npm
- Updated `package.json` to include the new dependency
- Updated `package-lock.json` with resolved dependencies

### 2. Code Changes
**Modified: `src/app/layout.tsx`**
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next";`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the `<body>` tag, placed after `{children}` and alongside the existing `<Analytics />` component

## Implementation Details

Since this project uses:
- **Next.js version**: 15.5.12 (newer than 13.5+)
- **Router type**: App Router (layout.tsx in src/app/)
- **Package manager**: npm (package-lock.json)

I followed the recommended approach for Next.js 13.5+ with App Router:
1. Imported `SpeedInsights` from `@vercel/speed-insights/next`
2. Added the component directly to the root layout without needing a separate client component
3. Placed it inside the `<body>` tag for optimal performance tracking

## Verification

✅ **Build Test**: Successfully built the project with `npm run build`
- Build completed without errors
- Static pages generated successfully
- TypeScript types validated correctly

✅ **Lock Files**: package-lock.json updated with new dependencies

## Files Modified
1. `omni-zkp-web/package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
2. `omni-zkp-web/package-lock.json` - Updated with resolved dependencies
3. `omni-zkp-web/src/app/layout.tsx` - Added SpeedInsights import and component

## Notes
- The SpeedInsights component is positioned alongside the existing Vercel Analytics component
- No breaking changes to existing functionality
- The component will automatically track Core Web Vitals and route changes
- Implementation follows Vercel's official documentation for Next.js App Router
